			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2024</a> paper:</span><br><i>Type Checking with Rewriting Rules</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/DimiRacordon.html">Dimi Racordon</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1145/3687997.3695640">10.1145/3687997.3695640</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1b.html"><span class="tagM">T1B: Static Semantics</span></a><ul><li> The paper casts type checking (for type-class style constraints) as a rewriting-based process over types/constraints.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5d.html"><span class="tagL">T5D: Formal Methods</span></a><ul><li> Rewriting rules provide a formal, analyzable framework for specifying and reasoning about the type system.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3a.html"><span class="tagL">T3A: Meta-languages</span></a><ul><li> The approach effectively defines a meta-level rule language for expressing typing and constraint resolution.
</li></ul></li></ul>
